		 	<span id="comment_score_64369466" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64369466); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~TractorBarry">TractorBarry</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~TractorBarry">( 788340 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64369466">		
		on Thursday April 04, 2024 @09:24AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//search.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23279538&amp;cid=64369466">#64369466</a>)
		<small><a href="http://www.jollyboyscc.org.uk/" title="http://www.jollyboyscc.org.uk/" class="user_homepage_display">Homepage</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64369466"><p>Following their change to "scrolling results on a single page" I now find Google search wholly unusable.  Previously you'd get a list of paged results so, if you weren't looking to buy something (which I'm not 90% of the time) then you'd use a sort of "binary chop" to get to the first page of results you were interested in.</p><p>e.g. After you got the first page back you could then jump directly to, say, page 5.  If this was still full of promoted advertising/SEO crap then you could jump to page 10.  If this contained decent results you could back jump to page 8, if not you could jump forward to page 15 etc.  Repeat a few times until you found the first page of reasonable results after which you could start going through them a page at a time - eventually finding what you're interested in.</p><p>Now with the "all results scroll on a single page" model you can only sequentially add the next page of results to the current page.  By the time you've clicked "more results" a good few times the page has become a bloated mess which gets slower and slower and it's simply impossible to find any decent results.  The more obscure the thing you're interested in the worse this gets.</p><p>So, Google search is currently totally unusable for me<nobr> <wbr></nobr>:(</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64369466">
